reviewText: I remember feeling pleased at the time at how funny and inventive this extended episode of The Fairly Odd Parents was the first time I saw it when it originally aired in 2004. Unfortunately, purchasing it for a second viewing proved to be a disappointment because a.) I had to put up with the brash, scatterbrain characteristics of the writing of an average Fairly Odd Parents episode (read "shrill"), b.) those characteristics were not suited for an episode longer than the average episode's length, and c.) the plotline wandered aimlessly from one send-up of a revered kiddie show to the next. The thing just needed tighter writing, basically, between the spot-on variety provided for the targets of its admiration (Jonny Quest, Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer, and Blue's Clues, among others). And short shrift was given the Rudolph' segment as it was decided to use the most basic of computer animation for this part of the story. With the love and attention the animators provided other segments, it was simply off-putting that they wouldn't employ stop-motion animation like that used for the original and show a little respect. Looking back, way back, I must have been doing the dishes the first time I saw the thing and was looking over my shoulder at a show that was thoroughly entertaining my young (now nearly grown) children, and there was some kind of infectious fun and merriment in the air. By the way, my order of the DVD came with a somewhat tarnished surface, probably a testament to how long it had been sitting around in a warehouse somewhere. I tried Windex and a soft cotton cloth to wipe away what appeared to be a white film, but no luck. It played alright, so I didn't feel the need to return it. I still wish I could get my money back. My kids, having moved on to other forms of media for their entertainment, refused to watch the episode with me when it arrived. Oh, well. I guess I can wait for the grandkids to come along someday and foist it off on them.

reviewText: This is a pretty good movie for a TV show, and also rather entertaining because of all the TV shows it parodies. Timmy is framed by Vicky for a lot of stuff, Mom and Dad won't listen, so Timmy decides, screw it all, and let's go where there's no adults! So he escapes through the TV and travels through various shows to try to find a good place to stay where he can do whatever he wants. Lots of classic shows are parodied and in rather humorous waysRugrats (becomes Carpet Critters)Strawberry Shortcake (becomes Paula Poundcake)Blue's Clues (becomes Clint's Hints)Jonny QuestThe FlintstonesThe JetsonsScooby Doo (UGH!)Peanuts (The Peanuts Christmas special becomes a Hanukah Special in the parody)Bugs BunnySpace GhostSpeed RacerTom and JerryTeenage Mutant Ninja Turtles (becomes something something cows, I forge the full title)Batman... and even Dragonball! (becomes Maho Mushi) Attack names are shouted out here, and in one attack Timmy shouts out Miyazaki - a surprising but welcome homage to Hayao Miyazaki, the man responsible for such enthralling films as My Neighbor Totoro, Spirited Away, Castle in the Sky, Kiki's Delivery Service, and Howl's Moving Castle.Each parody highlights and spoofs things from the original show that made it so famous, such as the limited animation in Speed Racer, the babies in Rugrats, the cartoon violence in Tom and Jerry (which earned a comment from Cosmo on the surprising amount of violence displayed in 1940's cartoons) and so on and so forth.All in all, this is a really entertaining movie. My only complaint is that they had Scooby Doo in here, all in all, a definite good movie if you like the TV show.

reviewText: I just often know how much animation has been with kids all over, and there are sometimes where those stories can be put to parody. For Nickelodeon, they seemed to have master it very well with the success of their 2001 breakthrough, The Fairly OddParents. The show has been one of those few hits that really has came out of nowhere to creep up to everybody as one of the most recent popular hit shows out there for Nickelodeon. The show also has dawned a few hit television movies as well: Abracastastrophe: and the recently televised one Channel Chasers.Cahnnel Chasers deals with Timmy and his fairy godparents Cosmo & Wanda, as Timmy wants to just runs away from his family, after he feels very tired of his babysitter, Vicky ruining everything in his life, and blaming things on him. As Timmy escapes into television, his future self comes out of nowhere to warn him about Vicky entering the television signal as a attempt to rule the world, using of the magical remote controls Timmy wishes for. The story also includes parodies and charactures of famous shows on television including Looney Tunes, The Simpsons, Batman, Peanuts, and Space Ghost.As in the story, Timmy's parents go out and search all over, not knowing Timmy was telling the truth about Vicky, and they do whatever it takes to make sure they still love him, and admit they were wrong about Timmy. The feeling of the story goes very well, and it proves that parents should listen to their kids much more than they think.All in all, The Fairly Odd Parents: Channel Chasers is a very well created made for TV movie. If you've seen it on Nickelodeon, you definitely might want to get this on DVD. The story is just great, and very enjoyable. If you don't have Nickelodeon, you might want to get that before wanting to get this DVD.Story: B+Animation: A-Overall DVD: B+500th review!!!

reviewText: THE FAIRLY ODD PARENTS! CHANNEL CHASERS was a tv movie of the FAIRLY ODD PARENTS! In this story, after Timmy's parents refuse to listen to him after he gets in trouble for problems caused by his evil babysitter Vicky and when he's grounded from tv, Timmy decides he wants to live in tv. Kids in tv never seem to have to listen to grown-ups. Meanwhile, a time-traveler from the future is after Timmy and trying to prevent a dystopian world ruled by Vicky from ever happening.CHANNEL CHASERS is a highly entertaining long episode of THE FAIRLY ODD PARENTS! It's got all the usual humor of the show, but then takes it up a notch. CHANNEL CHASERS makes allusions to THE TERMINATOR and STAR WARS. Also, the shows that are parodied as Timmy jumps from tv show to tv show include a huge variety: THE JETSONS, RUGRATS, FAT ALBERT, JONNY QUEST, STRAWBERRY SHORTCAKE, PEANUTS, SPACE GHOST, THE FLINTSTONES, SPEED RACER, SCOOBY DOO, BATMAN AND ROBIN, BLUE'S CLUES, TOM AND JERRY, LOONEY TUNES, SESAME STREET, TEENAGE MUTANT NINJA TURTLES, and DRAGON BALL Z. Personally, my favorite parody was "Poppyseed Avenue" (the parody of SESAME STREET) because all of the cartoon characters are seen as felt hand puppets. As a bonus treat, Alec Baldwin makes a special voice appearance on the episode.There are three bonus episodes included on the CHANNEL CHASERS disc. These are:"Spaced Out" – when playing Crash Nebula, Timmy wishes for an alien to play with and Mark Chang, the Prince of Yugopotaimia appears. He soon falls in love with Vicky. Wanda and Cosmo can't interfere in true love, so Timmy has to figure out of a different way to get rid of Mark."Microphony" – during the first weeks of summer, Vicky is ruining the kids summer vacation because of all the radio ads for her babysitting service. Timmy wishes for a magic microphone in order to fight back."This Is Your Wish" – set up my his mother, Cosmo appears on a game show in Fairy Land where the audience will get to decide if he gets to stay a fairy with Wanda and Timmy or goes home to live with his mom!In addition to the four episodes, there are a few other features. These include the "How to Draw Timmy" feature that illustrates how a person can draw Timmy; the deleted "If I Lived in T.V.!"  music video; and an outtake of the puppet parody.

reviewText: That's what I'd say to anyone considering buying this movie. If you enjoy silly, clever cartoons that also have characters you can really love, you might like watching "The Fairly Oddparents." And if you do like watching it, you'll flip for "Channel Chasers." Hysterically funny thanks to beloved Timmy Turner, Wanda, Cosmo, and the rest of the gang, and *outrageously* funny thanks to crazy good parodies of classic cartoons and various animation styles, "Channel Chasers" is, like the Fairly Oddparents themselves, perfect for both children and adults.From anime, to the 'Chucky Black Hannukah Special,' to Scooby Doo in which Scooby talks like Snoop Dog, to a BRILLIANT depiction of the Rankin/Bass Rudolph Christmas classic featuring Timmy, Cosmo, and Wanda, among perhaps a dozen others, "Channel Chasers" follows a coherent story besprinkled with the hilarious wisecracks and comments and adorable interaction typical of the show's characters. It's funny, it's creative, and yes, it's touching. What else would one expect from such a terrific cartoon? I give "Channel Chasers" two thumbs way up, and I say "rock on!" to the Fairly Oddparents.
